			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>danille wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Meets wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I posted this on teh eq forums, but jus posting my opinions here as well for those who dont read both:
<br />

<br />
I must say seems a really nice list of good issues i'd like to see changed. However I find it disturbing that none of them directly addresses magicians in PvP, only indirectly as new tools, as I play on VZ.  Necro/druid/shaman DoT's are landing very easily now, and they do the full 2/3 dmg until they are dispelled/cured, including curses that we have no way to cure in a 1 v 1 fight, while at the high end there doesnt seem to be a noticable change with my nukes, most of which are resisted or land for less than 1/10 of full damage.  What we received mostly from the patch (pvp wise that is) is that our pets are more resistant now to snare/root, which i believe is something that should have been there in the first place.  However, the pet would die to a high end druid/ranger from DS even without heals, due to the 2/3 dmg that it does in pvp acting like a spell. 
<br />
 
<br />
 Also, I notice when root actually lands on my pet it lasts for a few seconds before breaking, which is good, but snare on the otherhand lasts the full PvE duration, up to 14 mins for dru/ranger snares, while the max duration so far seems to be 30 seconds or so for a PC being snared by another PC.  Basically what this adds up to is all the other classes are both enjoying and receiving the blunt end of the new "easier to land spells" resists, increased melee range, decreased AC in pvp, and shortened durations on certain spells such as mezz and snare, while mages seem to only reap the benefit from an increased resistance for pets while not seeing the nukes landing any easier, and our #1 defense, our pets, are not seeing any of the snare/mezz duration changes.
<br />
 
<br />
I see a simple solution to this.  I can see how having both a pet AND spells that land can be over powering (although necros and shamans have this albeit their pets are weaker),  However, that leaves room for improvement in our pets, since it is afterall our only line of defense.  They can make the decreased AC in PvP apply to our pets too, so our pets miss less and hit for max more often, which might help against those DS's, as well as help against the high end melees who regen faster than our pets can damage them.  They can make the pets have the same pvp duration when snared/mezzed as players. They can give our pets the same 50% increased melee range that players enjoy.  Ideally they would give us all of these for compensation for spells that hardly land at high end.
<br />

<br />
Overall good compilation though, hope they hear us out.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Hi Meets,
<br />

<br />
I understand your concerns. Here is what I suggest. 
<br />

<br />
1) Create a new post (in its own thread) on these boards detailing the pet changes changes you want made.
<br />
2) Make a quick short list of bullet points that you want addressed that I can cut and past as a PvP footnote under the last item #10.
<br />
3) I will repost the list for the PvP pet concerns in the correspondent section and ask Brenlo to address it.
<br />

<br />
Just wanted to make you aware that I did send a PM to Phroak_VZ (a wizzy) who is the PvP correspondent, on SoE's website with a link to the PvP issues on this website that developed since the new PvP rules went into effect. That PM and link dealt just with the resists on nukes though and not the effects on pets.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Changes I'd like to see made:
<br />

<br />
1 -  Make our pet's pvp targets -20% AC, just like how melees get the negative AC check against pvp targets, to negate high end melees regenning at the same rate or faster than our pet can damage.
<br />

<br />
2 -  Treat pets as *melee* damage as pvp melee damage and pet spell/proc damage as pvp *spell* damage, i.e. doing the full 100% rather than 66% melee damage, with 50% increased range in pvp, but treat their procs/spells as pvp *spell* damage, doing 66%, max of 40% of target's total HP, which currently does 100%. <span style="font-weight: bold">(It Is Currently REVERSED)</span>
<br />

<br />
3 -  Have the separate durations for spells such as snare and enthrall in pvp apply to our pets as well, i.e. atm Entrap lasts under 1 minute in pvp, but 14 minutes on our pets still.
<br />

<br />
Any high end Zek mages like to comment/add? Are there even more than a handful of Zek mages left? I feel a mage should have a pet to perform melee damage, although not nearly as high as a melee class, while we, the master, dish out the spell damage.  Although the current spell resists on DD's are frustrating in 1 v 1 encounters even after malosinia lands at the high end, i can see how changing it can overpower us in mass pvp, where all it would take is 4-5 nukers to simultaneously nuke the MA's target.  That means the fix should be in our pet damage in PvP, which in its current state falls severely short on upholding its side of the bargain.<br />_________________<br />Meetmefrend
<br />

